[thinking] **Considering logging adjustments**
[thinking] 
[thinking] I’m thinking about how tests shouldn’t make global changes. Maybe SpringApplication could use logging system reflection, but I don't see any harm. To reduce logging output, perhaps the app code could create SpringApplication before running and set `setLogStartupInfo(false)` and `setBannerMode(Mode.OFF)`. I’ll need to remember to import SpringApplication and Banner.Mode for this to work properly. Just need to keep everything organized!
[thinking] 
[thinking] **Considering Spring's AOT behavior**
[thinking] 
[thinking] I'm trying to understand how Spring's bean factory can instantiate non-public classes by default. For AOT, the code might be generated in the same package, allowing access to package-private constructors. ApplicationContextAotGenerator might introspect here, which could be fine. To avoid registering a source class as a bean, perhaps I could use `SpringApplicationBuilder().sources()`. But this needs to align with the primary source in the AOT processor. Can the generated app class just call `SpringApplication.run(EmptyConfiguration.class, args)` instead?
[thinking] 
[thinking] **Exploring SpringApplication options**
[thinking] 
[thinking] I'm considering how the main method of the app can run a SpringApplication with another primary source. It seems there are no restrictions on running it this way, which avoids registering package-private classes. But I'll need a configuration class. A public nested static class could work. Alternatively, I might use a package-private top-level configuration without annotations. Although creating the context manually is an option, the AOT hook only intercepts `SpringApplication.withHook`, which still requires a SpringApplication.
[thinking] 
