[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Considering logging adjustments**\n\nI’m thinking about how tests shouldn’t make global changes. Maybe SpringApplication could use logging system reflection, but I don't see any harm. To reduce logging output, perhaps the app code could create SpringApplication before running and set `setLogStartupInfo(false)` and `setBannerMode(Mode.OFF)`. I’ll need to remember to import SpringApplication and Banner.Mode for this to work properly. Just need to keep everything organized!\n\n**Considering Spring's AOT behavior**\n\nI'm trying to understand how Spring's bean factory can instantiate non-public classes by default. For AOT, the code might be generated in the same package, allowing access to package-private constructors. ApplicationContextAotGenerator might introspect here, which could be fine. To avoid registering a source class as a bean, perhaps I could use `SpringApplicationBuilder().sources()`. But this needs to align with the primary source in the AOT processor. Can the generated app class just call `SpringApplication.run(EmptyConfiguration.class, args)` instead?\n\n**Exploring SpringApplication options**\n\nI'm considering how the main method of the app can run a SpringApplication with another primary source. It seems there are no restrictions on running it this way, which avoids registering package-private classes. But I'll need a configuration class. A public nested static class could work. Alternatively, I might use a package-private top-level configuration without annotations. Although creating the context manually is an option, the AOT hook only intercepts `SpringApplication.withHook`, which still requires a SpringApplication.", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_02910d8b2c0c8ff6016a24bed2b27c819080b6b9db61788415\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"content\":[],\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABqJL7yjK5kwHyodmSKY7SzvGt2frpSjt8bqZSOOKO6D-4OMmVygQeNUA9jiNWALK5UWlODZD